value.value: Tissue that is part of some adrenal gland.
Anatomical region lying to the posteiror or ventral side of the metapterygial axis.
Region of the humerus associated with the biceps attachment areas.
Ridge shaped projection, similar to the keel of a boat.
Distinct colored area on the caudal region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.
Anatomical structure consisting of a pattern of ridges on an osteoderm.
A dermal scale that is found in the head region.
A scale part of the cheek scale row.
A row of scales foudn in the cheek region of the head of an organism.
Grooves on the palatine bone which denote the passage of the choana or internal naris.
Pelvic clasper organs that have been modified into a flattened structure.
Facet on the anterior surface of the calcaneus (as called calcaneum) for the articulation of the cuboid bone.
Osteoderm found on the dorsal surface of an organisms.
A depression on the lateral surface of the braincase posterior to the Vidian canal (Conrad 2008).
Section of the oviduct external to the uterine wall.
A sesamoid bone located near or in the flexor musculature of a joint.
Foramen that allows the passge of the glossopharyngeal nerve (cranial nerve IX).
Fourth most proximal phalanx in manual or pedal digits.
Area on the otic capsule for the articulation of the hyoid.
Caudal fin radial element located ventral to the notochord.
Radial element that is part of the caudal fin.
Situated just caudal to the acetabulum, the foramen is bound dorsally by the illium and ventrally by the ischium. The foramen transmitts the ischiadic nerves and vessels (Baumel et al. 1993).
The condyloid fossa on the cranial aspect of the Atlas my be perforated (foramen fossa) or have an open dorsal notch (Incisura fossa) in which the apex of the dens rides. (From Baumel et al. 1993).
The region on the palate corresponding to the location of the pterygoid bone, if present and between the palatine bones and the parasphenoid if not.
Open space between on the palate between the pteryogoid bone and the parasphenoid.
A joint in the lower jaw that enhances kinesis and for swallowing prey. Allows enhanced mobility and intraramal bending to increase gape.
Elongate bar consisting of fused quadratojugal and jugal and connecting the maxilla to the quadrate.
Distinct cartilage around the jaws of elasmobranchs.
Condyle on the lateral side of the quadrate.
One of the branches of the dorsal aorta, after it enters the aortic canal.
The triangular shaped posterior fold at the angle of the mouth. From Chakrabarty 2006.
The medialmost condyle on the distal region of the quadrate, in contact with the pterygoid.
The medialmost of the cotyla of the lower jaw, for articulation with the cranium.

An embryonic fissure between the otic capsule and the arches which develop into the occipital bones. The fissure may persist into adulthood. It is also referred to as the 'lateral otic fissure' The metotic fissure opens into the vestibular fontanelle, if the fontanelle is present. (Johanson et al. (2003)). Otherwise it opens to the metotic foramen.
Distinct colored area on the midbody region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.
A bony projection of the premaxilla that extends cadually and separates the nasal bones.
Dorsal swelling on the head. Found in cichlid fish. Often only in males and during breeding season, but not exclusively so.

The wall of the fallopian tube includes an elaborately folded mucosa (endosalpinx) surrounded by a muscularis (myosalpinx). The mucosa is lined by a ciliated columnar epithelium with secretory cells, and is folded out into the lumen so that an ovum in the lumen will always be close to the cilia for transport to the uterus.
An anterior cusp on the stylar shelf of the tooth.
The stylar shelf is an an expansion of the cingulum; it often bears small cusps (each with its own name...).
A pronounced notch or cavity in the lateral face of the parietal.

Ventral process on the neurocranium for the articulation of upper pharyngeal bones. It is variably composed of the parasphenoid, basioccipital, and prootic depending on the species. From: Greenwood, PH (1978). A review of the pharyngeal hypophysis and its significance in the classification of African cichlid fishes. Bull. Br. Mus. Nat. Hist. (Zool.) 33: 297-323.
The lack of chondrification of the anterior wall of the cranial cavity in front of the pineal foramen.....(Hanken and Hall).

Cartilage arranged into tesserae, blocks of calcified cartilage that fit together as tiles on a floor form a mosaic. Found only in chondrichthyans. Reference: A. Peter Klimley. 2013. The Biology of Sharks and Rays. University of Chicago Press.
The convex articular surface on the qudrate, part of the craniomandibular joint.
As defined here, this refers to a depression on the lateral surface of the braincase posterior to the Vidian canal as opposed to the carotid fossa...(Conrad 2008).

Rictal bristles project from the beak of many insect-eating birds, including flycatchers, nightjars and even the American Robin. They are believed to provide protection for the bird's eyes as it consumes its wriggly prey. The bristles may also provide tactile feedback, like the whiskers on a dog or cat. from http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/studying/feathers/feathers/document_view.

An entotympanic that arises in forward part of tympanic floor. It may be intimately fused witA cartilage of tube during development(MacPhee (1981: 62)) in contrast to a caudal entotympanic arising in the rear tympanic floor. From O'Leary et al. 2012.
